Solution:

By the Angle Bisector Theorem, $\frac{BD}{DC} = \frac{AB}{AC} = \frac{5}{4}.$  Let $BD = 5x$ and $DC = 4x.$  Then $BC = 5x + 4x = 9x,$ so $x = \frac{5}{9}.$  Therefore, $BD = \frac{25}{9}$ and $DC = \frac{20}{9}.$

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C, D;

A = (0,2);
B = (-1,0);
C = (1,0);
D = extension(B, B + dir(135), C, C + dir(45));

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--D);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, S);
label("$5$", (A + B)/2, NW);
label("$5$", (A + C)/2, NE);
label("$4$", (B + C)/2, S);
label("$\frac{25}{9}$", (B + D)/2, SW);
label("$\frac{20}{9}$", (C + D)/2, SE);
[/asy]

By the Law of Cosines on triangle $ABD,$
\[AD^2 = AB^2 + BD^2 - 2 \cdot AB \cdot BD \cdot \cos \angle ABD.\]By the Law of Cosines on triangle $ABC,$
\[AC^2 = AB^2 + BC^2 - 2 \cdot AB \cdot BC \cdot \cos \angle ABC.\]Since $\angle ABD = \frac{1}{2} \angle ABC,$
\[\cos \angle ABD = \sqrt{\frac{1 + \cos \angle ABC}{2}}.\]Then
\[\cos \angle ABC = \frac{AB^2 + BC^2 - AC^2}{2 \cdot AB \cdot BC} = \frac{5^2 + 5^2 - 4^2}{2 \cdot 5 \cdot 5} = \frac{17}{25},\]so
\[\cos \angle ABD = \sqrt{\frac{1 + \frac{17}{25}}{2}} = \frac{7}{5 \sqrt{2}}.\]Hence,
\begin{align*}
AD^2 &= 5^2 + \left( \frac{25}{9} \right)^2 - 2 \cdot 5 \cdot \frac{25}{9} \cdot \frac{7}{5 \sqrt{2}} \\
&= \frac{2500}{81} - \frac{175 \sqrt{2}}{9} \\
&= \frac{2500 - 1575 \sqrt{2}}{81} \\
&= \boxed{\frac{2500 - 1575 \sqrt{2}}{81}}.
\end{align*}

